      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Memorial Designs: A Fitting Tribute?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lynn Jericho letter says eight finalists for design of World Trade Center memorial minimize historical and spiritual significance of event and place (Nov 20 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Almost 3,000 lives were lost in New York on Sept. 11. We mourn their loss and feel profound compassion for their families and friends. But 9/11 calls out for a memorial that symbolizes far more than the tragic loss of life.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Almost 3,000 lives were lost in New York on Sept. 11. We mourn their loss and feel profound compassion for their families and friends. But 9/11 calls out for a memorial that symbolizes far more than the tragic loss of life.</p>
        <p>The jury has chosen eight designs that offer little recognition of an event that has changed the world and any imagination of a future for all humanity (front page, Nov. 20).</p>
        <p>Lacking any creative differences, the designs minimize the historical and spiritual significance of the event and the place.</p>
        <p>As works of sacred art, world inspiration or personal meaning, all the designs fail.</p>
        <p>Among the 5,201 submissions, surely there were creative possibilities that went beyond the focus on memory of the dead and offered imaginations for the living and the world they must create.</p>
        <p>LYNN JERICHO  Jersey City, Nov. 20, 2003</p>
        <p>The writer is the author of a book about ground zero.</p>
      </block>
